WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
And now we can begin, so please join me in welcoming Larry Fenn.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
So I'll get right to it.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
I'll just say a little brief bit about myself.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
I'm going to talk about journalism at the Associated Press.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.000
We use R, at least on the data team, pretty much to do every part of our workflow.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:32.000
We really couldn't do it without R and RStudio and the libraries that exist for R.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Brief high-level summary, the AP is a not-for-profit cooperative news agency.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:41.000
I'm a data journalist on the data team.

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:47.000
And so typical AP coverage includes but is not limited to breaking news.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.000
So that is, like, non-negotiable.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:50.000
That's part of our blood.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:55.000
That's kind of, you know, when photographers run out to grab a camera, we, as nerdy as it sounds,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
go looking for data, go looking for the story in the data.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.000
You know, it's a train crash, we look up level-crossing data, stuff like that.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:04.000
We also cover investigative reporting.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:09.000
So that's sort of your long-form deep dives into complex or large data sets.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
Something else about the scope of what we do, it's pretty much every level you can imagine geographically,

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.000
local, municipal issues, all the way up to international.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:24.000
Another big thing, and I think this is in common with a lot of journalism news agencies,

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
not just the AP, but there's collaboration both inside with domain experts who are not necessarily so tech-savvy

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
or data-savvy, but also collaboration outside.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:38.000
People who, again, with a wide variety of backgrounds and levels of expertise,

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.000
and it's very important to try to synthesize these viewpoints together.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:44.000
And finally, what is it that we produce?

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:51.000
At the AP, we produce pretty much everything you can imagine from data, text copy, graphics, broadcast graphics,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
social, interactive experiences, like the fancy ones you see on the web.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
We try to do that, too.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.000
So that's just a high-level overview of what it is that we do.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Here's sort of what I'll just try to cover.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:08.000
I'm leaving a lot of stuff out because there is a whole lot out of scope on how journalism works.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:11.000
But when it comes to data analysis, let's start.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So first we'll talk about how we load in the data.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
So there's a couple of cool, really remarkable tools that are makes available to us.

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.000
First is dbPlyer.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.000
I don't know if people are familiar with this one.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
This is a really great, really great library.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:30.000
So in particular, when you have data sets that are extremely large.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So this was the Arcos pharmaceutical database.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
I believe it's some hundreds of millions of rows.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
It's something that you couldn't, even with a laptop like this one, you really couldn't work with it feasibly.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:45.000
So we have it hosted, and then you can see here there's a sort of connection to it.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.000
And just to, this is not necessarily like a tutorial session.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:52.000
But the cool thing about it is once you run this code, you get this connection.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And the way the connection behaves with dbPlyer is it behaves basically like a data frame.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
But you'll see here it says database.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
And so the idea is you're still able to use all those verbs you're used to from the tidyverse.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
But you're hitting some SQL database somewhere in the world.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
Really useful, incredibly useful for us.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Another one is Google Forms and Google Sheets.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:22.000
So this is often what we need to do when we collect data for a story because the data doesn't exist.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:29.000
You know, it's kind of awe-inspiring that we don't have to pay for Mechanical Turk.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:34.000
We can just sit down and distribute work between ourselves and sort of digest it all.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:37.000
And so the workflow there, the way it looks, I'm just going to show it off a bit.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
We were doing this story about NFL injuries.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And, you know, it's out there. That data's out there.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
But we wanted to make sure we were counting exactly what it is that we wanted to count

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
and drawing the lines where we wanted to draw.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
So we came up with our own little survey that we could then hand out to reporters

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
and then we could all put it together like a sort of human-powered MapReduce.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:59.000
You turn that crank and you get this great data sheet at the end.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
And then you plug into it using Google Sheets 4.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So that looks like this.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
And if you've used Google Sheets 4, it's pretty straightforward.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
There's an OAuth step, but you just do read sheet and then you get the data right away, ready to go.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So that's another thing we do.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:16.000
Last is HTTR for APIs.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:22.000
So that's both including ones that exist in the world, like the BLS, the Labor Statistics API, the Census API.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:28.000
But also we have homebrewed, again, databases and, you know, data admin tools.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:32.000
One that I'll call out here is we were sort of looking at mass killings

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
and we have this whole system that sort of we rolled our own

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.000
and use HTTR to get the authentication token and to get the data files

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:45.000
or to get the relevant data off of the mass killings database that we rolled.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
The use case here, of course, is, you know, we often collaborate with other organizations.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And so building, you know, it seems like overkill, but building a standalone data admin tool

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:58.000
actually does save a lot of headaches with collaborating with other large organizations.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
The next thing is template graphics.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:04.000
This is something that we are doing and we want to do more of.

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:07.000
And, you know, it's an endless struggle to make better and better.

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
But so the convenient thing for us is there's an existing newsroom style guide, right?

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
We're not the first people to do graphs, right?

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
But that means it's really easy for us, for me, you know,

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:22.000
for us to kind of develop using ggplot a theme, a theme package.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
We just follow very prescriptively what the style guide is.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:28.000
And so this is actually available on the Associated Press GitHub

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:31.000
if you want to kind of ape the graphical style.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
GitHub.com slash Associated Press slash AP theme.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
You may not have this proprietary font.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.000
My apologies.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
You'll have to substitute for some other font.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:45.000
But the cool thing is this also facilitates conversation between us

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
and the other sort of graphics-able people in the newsroom

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.000
because, you know, we can say, all right, does this work?

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:54.000
You know, is this the style of graphic we want to make?

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
How does this comport with our style guidelines?

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
And that conversation with ggplot, that prototyping was so quick

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
that, you know, working it out.

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And once we have that theme in hand, you can just, you know,

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:07.000
come up with graphics basically as often as you have the idea for them.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:11.000
The other thing is we had to make sure it fit into the existing publishing workflows.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:12.000
So we have a lot of artists.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:13.000
They use Illustrator.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.000
They use vector graphics.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
And so it was really handy in the R universe

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:20.000
that you can just export these graphics like vector graphics.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Perfect as far as plugging into how things already work.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
So next we'll talk about reporting the findings.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:34.000
So R Markdown has come up already in some of these case study presentations.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
And, you know, it's pretty much the same story here.

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:38.000
People are in a hurry.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.000
No matter who we're trying to tell, you know, internally, externally,

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
no one has time to read stuff.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:45.000
So R Markdown is a crucial tool to help condense

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
what would otherwise be this sort of long, detailed, rambling notebook

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
into a very condensed, concise thing.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
The other advantage, we used to roll our own things

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:55.000
before R Markdown and R Notebooks came around.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:56.000
We'd make these web pages.

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:57.000
We'd make these graphics.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
It was a nightmare trying to make it work for people

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:01.000
who were trying to browse these things on their, you know,

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:02.000
at home on an iPad or something.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:03.000
Terrible.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
But with R Markdown, you know, it's just a set of really handy existing

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:11.000
sort of templates and tools that we can plug into.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:16.000
So let me just show off kind of the one, just an example one.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
So the NFL injuries ended up being, you know,

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:22.000
turned into something simple like this so that we can hand to whoever

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
is new joining the project, like, hey, we're going to catch you up.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:26.000
Like, this is what we've already got.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:28.000
This is what we're studying, you know,

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and this is where we're going to go with the story.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
So really handy.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
DT, that data table that you see at the top here, great.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.000
We love it.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
There's the filters.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.000
You can also style it.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:41.000
We don't really do it that often, but you can sort of selectively

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
highlight, like, oh, make all the ones that are above a certain size bold.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
It's really quite handy.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And then Leaflet for maps, you know, oftentimes I think a map

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
is not really the right tool for the job, but no doubt it can be

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
a very useful tool in data exploration when you first get a data set

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.000
to at least see what is going on inside your data set.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
So that's where we're using R Markdown pretty heavily,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:09.000
and it's, again, we've made our own R Markdown template,

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:11.000
and it's also on the Associated Press GitHub

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
if you want to just steal it.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So I'll just sort of wrap up.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
I think there's future directions.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
So things are not perfect.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:21.000
We're still working on it.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:24.000
One big one you might not have noticed here is interactive.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
So static graphics seems to be in hand.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Interactive graphics, not so much.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:34.000
We've explored GGI raft, plotly, you know, bokeh,

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:37.000
some sort of GG plot to D3 conversion.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:41.000
There's kind of still, you know, we're missing that kind of key piece

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
there that kind of fits.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
Part of this is maybe what we need out of it,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
not necessarily like I'm not claiming that there's no good

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
R interactive web graphic workflow.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
That's not true.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
But for our particular case, it's been sort of still a question

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
of finding the right tool for the job there.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:08:59.000
Automation, got to have that buzzword,

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:02.000
but the two big ones we're talking about, one is recurring data.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
So some stories, they keep happening, right?

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:08.000
Spring housing, labor statistics, that stuff is recurring.

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
It's from an API.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
We can get better and better at closing that loop

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
and making it so that, you know, when the data comes in,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:17.000
there's a minor, there's a human involved somewhere

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
to make sure that the data is, you know, correct.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
But then other than that, all the other work has already been done

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
and we package it up.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
The other big one, yeah, this touches on it,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
is we want to make sort of a data validation thing.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
Again, not to remove the human element from the whole story

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
because it's impossible to come up with some sort of magic script

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
that will catch all the errors in your data,

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:39.000
but just simple stuff like how many different types

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
of white space characters are going on in this data file.

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Does this data file do day, month, year, or month, year, day,

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.000
or month, day, year, you know, catching those kinds of problems

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
before they become a real issue, sort of.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:55.000
I know that there are certain, like, people have made some efforts

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:58.000
in this space and we're still working on trying to either contribute

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.000
or latch on to an existing solution there.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:04.000
Working with Python, I know, boo, but there are other people

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.000
in the organization who work with Python.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:09.000
They make graphics, they do all these other reports in them,

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.000
and thanks to packages like Reticulate, you know,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.000
we haven't done it yet, but hopefully it's not far off

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
that we can bridge that gap within our organization as well,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and that'll be a pretty outstanding moment when we get there.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And then lastly, the AP does this very particular thing

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:28.000
where we hand out data to member papers and news orgs

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
to then localize stories for themselves,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
and we believe that R could be a really...

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:37.000
We could automate a lot more of that also using R to script

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
and to control it. We don't think we need anything more than R

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
to achieve that goal.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
With that, that's just the... that's it.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
Yeah, that's the summary. Any questions?

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
Any questions?

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:53.000
Thank you again, Larry.

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
Yeah, a few questions to come through.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
So the first one is, how do you export plots as vector graphics?

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Oh, yeah.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:04.000
If you have SVG Lite,

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and you do need to get installed with that,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
so that's like a system dependency,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
but when you're doing, like, a ggplot...

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So, yeah, here, I have this all in this AP theme script.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
You see here when you call the ggsave function,

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:24.000
if you just make the file name end with SVG, it does it.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:27.000
Now, that is to say, though, there is one caveat.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:31.000
The graphic artists don't really like the SVGs that are, really,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
SVG Lite spits out,

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:36.000
and so that's one thing we are also looking into trying to improve.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:38.000
Basically, there's... it's subpar.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:43.000
It doesn't quite line up with the way they like their project files to look.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
But just make the file name end with SVG

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
and follow the error messages if it doesn't work.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
Right.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
All right, next question.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
When your team hires, are they looking for journalism experience?

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:00.000
How important are writing skills versus data analysis skills?

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:05.000
That's tricky because I was hired because of my background in this,

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
but there are definitely...

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:11.000
the team's core is about writing more than anything else.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
I think if we were looking...

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
you know, if we were thinking about, you know,

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
what is more in demand,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:22.000
there's still this question of news judgment

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
because, to pull back the veil,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:30.000
we don't do a lot of Bayesian analysis or neural network modeling.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
We really don't.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
We would love to, but the reality is,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
stories have to be comprehensible to everyone,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
and so that kind of ties behind our back

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
the degree to which we can really use advanced statistics

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
and mathematical knowledge.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
All right, next question.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.000
How do you get involved in doing data analysis for journalism?

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:58.000
So, I think one on-ramp that has been kind of cool

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
is there's a lot of state-level, in particular, open data communities.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
These are people who get together

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
and maybe it's something as simple as election results

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
or maybe it's something more complicated like lead testing results.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
If you look on GitHub, there are a surprising amount of

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
sort of state open data communities

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
that are all about, you know, in their state,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
doing data projects off of that.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And I think if you, you know,

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
if someone wanted to pursue an interesting story,

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:29.000
you know, that might be the easiest way to at least get started.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.000
I don't know how you could make money with it,

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
but you could certainly start investigating things at the state level

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
by reaching out to people, folks who, you know, work in open data.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.000
Stuff like K-12 education, public health,

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:45.000
that stuff is all, like, those data sets are all out there

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:48.000
waiting for people to find stories in them.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Cool, thank you.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
How about, how can you convince your management

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
of allocating time and resources to developing work like this

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.000
in R that may be costly up front?

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
That's a tricky one, yeah.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:05.000
We, at least in the history of when I started,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:09.000
it oftentimes was a matter of building good partnerships

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
within the company.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
So you're not going to be able to get this project off the ground,

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:17.000
but at least from the journalism perspective, you know,

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
if there was already a strong investigative project

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:23.000
that you could identify had a strong data angle,

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
that is sort of the on-ramp there,

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
because then you can tangibly show, like,

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
how much better the story is with the data angle.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.000
You know, your mileage may vary in different organizations.

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:38.000
Final couple of questions, I think they're from the same person,

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
so I'm just going to ask them together.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:45.000
If other media rely on Associated Press for breaking stories,

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
any future for them also drawing on AP's code,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
example, for quick visualization to be rebranded?

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Also just curious, are you paging through your presentation notes

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
in a reporter's notebook?

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
Yeah, I do have a reporter's notebook.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
Absolutely.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
You got me dead to rights.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
You got me dead to rights.

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
For the code, yeah, we wanted to expand that as well.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
So we are already doing data distributions,

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:16.000
and we are partnered with this organization, Data.World,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
and they have a sort of web-based SQL browser,

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:22.000
and we give them SQL code out of the gate that they can use.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.000
But we definitely, you know, we believe strongly that, like,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:30.000
you know, reproducibility and, you know, distributing the code

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
and making it out there, at least for members,

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
hopefully eventually also for the public as well,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
so they can just, you know, grab the public data,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
grab the code we used,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
see the same exact things we saw in the story.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:43.000
That's definitely a future goal for us.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
Right now, yeah, unfortunately it's sort of limited

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
to whoever is interested.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
We can't, like, kick down people's doors

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:50.000
and force them to use R.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:56.000
I know that's, yeah.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
A few more coming in.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:01.000
Can you explain a little more about how you do data validation?

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:02.000
Right.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
So oftentimes, so what we're hoping to do

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:07.000
with the automated one is to catch really simple things,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.000
like oftentimes, for example, if you're working with someone,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:14.000
you're requesting data from them,

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
and they don't have the best data skills,

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
they maybe did something in Excel,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:21.000
and it truncated the data file at 1.2 million rows or whatever,

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.000
the Excel problem, right, picking up that that happened.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.000
That's something that we are hoping we can sort of build

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
into some scripting solution.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
More generally, though, how do we know that the data is right?

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
That is a long and tricky question,

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
and that is where we intersect with traditional journalism

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
because oftentimes, like, I'll look at K-12 data,

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
and you'll just see something.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
You'll do the usual data analysis and see the outlier

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
and be like, that's an extreme outlier.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:48.000
What's the next step?

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
You pick up the phone, and you call the superintendent

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
and be like, well, according to the survey data,

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
you put this number in, and then usually the superintendent

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
will be like, oh, that's not right.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:59.000
Or, you know, it's a soft process, unfortunately.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:01.000
I can't give you a cookbook for it,

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:03.000
but you just have to be constantly critical.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:05.000
And for a lot of the stories where it's really meaningful

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:10.000
and worth it, we will just, you know, ultimately make sure that,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
you know, let's say we're reporting on shootings.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
We'll go over every, you know, one of the 1,500 shootings

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
that are in our story to make sure we got it right.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.000
You know, follow up with the police department or something.

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:26.000
It takes a lot of time, and, you know, but that's, it's worth it.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Do you have any sort of peer review for your data analyses?

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:33.000
So within the organization, we definitely make sure, you know,

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
we have these principles that I think we've helpfully stolen

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
from other communities of, you know, second set of eyes,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
making sure that nothing hits the wire without, you know,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
multiple people's input on it.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:45.000
More broadly, though, when it comes to stories, you know,

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:48.000
we don't go as far as handing the story pre-written

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
to the people that it involves.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
But many times, you know, for example, for me, you know,

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
if I'm doing something about the Bureau of Labor Statistics,

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
I'll make sure to check in with the BLS economist

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.000
who prepared that data set and ask him,

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:02.000
is this a valid use of your data?

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:03.000
I'm trying to write this story.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:05.000
This is exactly how I've set it up.

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:07.000
I'm looking at these numbers and this, you know,

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
I'm trying to put it into this analysis,

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
and just asking the economist that prepared that data,

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
you know, up front, is this a valid use of the data?

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
And if he says, you know, no, you've got it all wrong,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:20.000
it's seasonally adjusted, you fool, then, you know, yeah.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
All right, I think we have time for one or two more.

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:28.000
What is your favorite data-driven story that you've worked on

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
with the AP and why?

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Ooh.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
Okay, there was one that was really hard but really rewarding.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:40.000
We talked about, it was about K-12 education demographics.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
It involved, you know, this big, big question,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
which is charter schools and, you know,

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:47.000
segregation by race and ethnicity.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:50.000
And while, you know, obviously controversial topic,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
one thing that I really wanted to make sure we could get across,

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
one thing that I needed to make sure was in that story

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
and in that data analysis,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
was to break the traditional approach of saying white, non-white.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Because I thought that that was, yeah, it makes the analysis easier

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
because you've reduced it to a binary sort of consideration.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
But that's absolutely not, in my opinion,

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
the right way to look at it.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:12.000
So it took a lot of time, but coming up with sort of new metrics

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:16.000
that captured the multidimensional nature of race and ethnicity,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
making sure we're using metrics that, you know, like,

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:23.000
you know, we kind of picked and stole the best ones from other fields of research.

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
But like, you know, how do people study housing segregation?

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:29.000
How do people study, you know, sort of distributions of noise and information theory?

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:32.000
What is the right way to represent similarity

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:35.000
in a way that's deeper than just saying white versus non-white?

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:39.000
Because so much of this country is not just a question of white versus non-white.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
We're about out of time. Thank you again, Larry Fenn.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:50.000
Thank you.

